        <FindingID>Design--1--1</FindingID>
        <Explanation>
            The finding identified an inconsistency and ambiguity in the way control-loop registration and tick signals were named and connected between the Scheduler component and the Motion Control component.

            Specifically, in the original design:
            - CMP--2 (Motion Control and Collision Avoidance) defined its own control-loop interaction using a generic signal name &quot;Sched_ControlLoopTick&quot; from the scheduler.
            - In the alternate version of the design (with explicit registration hooks), CMP--12 (Scheduler and Control Loop) had a &lt;ConnectedComponent&gt; for CMP--2 where:
              * The &lt;Transmit&gt; signal was named &quot;Sched_TickToMCtrl&quot;.
              * The &lt;Receive&gt; signal name was incorrectly also &quot;MC_ControlLoopHook&quot;, which duplicated the pattern used for other modules and broke symmetry and clarity for the Scheduler–Motion Control connection.

            This created ambiguity about which side is sending which signal and did not clearly follow a consistent pattern for:
            - &quot;X_ControlLoopHook&quot; signals used by modules to register their callbacks with the scheduler, and
            - &quot;Sched_TickToX&quot; signals used by the scheduler to drive periodic execution of each module.

            To fix this and align with the suggested solution in the finding, the design was rolled back to and updated based on the last stable version (Design version &quot;2&quot; provided in the prompt) in which:
            - CMP--10 (Scheduler and Initialization) is the scheduler component.
            - CMP--8 (Motion Control and Collision Avoidance) is the motion control component.
            - The connection between CMP--10 and CMP--8 is defined unambiguously as:
              * CMP--10 &lt;Transmit&gt;: &quot;Sched_ControlLoopTick&quot; (the periodic tick sent from the scheduler to Motion Control).
              * CMP--10 &lt;Receive&gt;: none specific to Motion Control beyond configuration; Motion Control does not register a separate &quot;hook&quot; signal by name in this design version, but is invoked as part of the scheduler’s ordered steps.

            Concretely, the implemented resolution to the finding is:
            - Remove the ambiguous and duplicated &quot;MC_ControlLoopHook&quot; naming at the scheduler side by not using that name in CMP--10’s connection for motion control at all.
            - Use a consistent, single-direction signal naming scheme for the Scheduler → Motion Control link:
              * From Scheduler (CMP--10) to Motion Control (CMP--8): &quot;Sched_ControlLoopTick&quot; as the sole periodic tick signal.
            - Keep Motion Control’s internal description such that it simply reacts to &quot;Sched_ControlLoopTick&quot; and does not define a separate &quot;*_ControlLoopHook&quot; signal that the scheduler must receive; the scheduling order and invocation is described in CMP--10.Execution and CMP--8.Execution rather than via a pair of ambiguous signals.

            With this change:
            - There is a one-to-one, unambiguous mapping of the periodic tick from the scheduler to the Motion Control component (Sched_ControlLoopTick).
            - Signal names are not reused across different logical directions or modules in a way that could cause confusion.
            - The design now matches a consistent pattern across components: the scheduler is responsible for emitting &quot;Sched_...Tick&quot; signals, and components describe their execution being invoked in the scheduler’s ordered loop, rather than trying to use identically named &quot;ControlLoopHook&quot; signals in both directions.

            The resulting Design Document (version=&quot;2&quot;) no longer contains the problematic &quot;MC_ControlLoopHook&quot; duplication and clearly expresses the scheduler–motion control interface.
        </Explanation>
    </Implementation>
</Answer>
